  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Withdrawing a property from the market happens more often than most sellers realise. Campaigns that fail to produce an acceptable offer, changes in personal circumstances mid-campaign, and sellers who simply change their minds are all common reasons properties come off the market before a sale is finalised. It is a legitimate decision and sometimes the right one. Understanding what it means legally, financially, and strategically before you act will help you make that call clearly and recover well.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why sellers withdraw</h2>
      <p>The most common reason sellers withdraw is that the campaign did not produce offers they were willing to accept. In a softer market, genuine buyer interest can be present without buyers reaching a price the vendor is comfortable with. Rather than accepting a price that does not meet their needs, sellers sometimes prefer to remove the property, reassess, and return when conditions have shifted.</p>

      <p>A change in personal circumstances is the second most common driver. Divorce proceedings, a change in employment, a health event, or a shift in housing plans can all make a sale no longer appropriate at a particular point in time. These situations are rarely planned, and they are not a failure of the campaign.</p>

      <p>Market deterioration during a campaign is a third scenario. If conditions change materially between listing and when offers arrive, some sellers prefer to withdraw rather than sell into a declining environment at a price that may look weak in hindsight.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Withdrawing versus letting the authority lapse</h2>
      <p>There is an important distinction between actively withdrawing your property and simply allowing your agency authority to expire at its end date. In Queensland, an open listing authority or an exclusive authority will have a fixed term. If you do nothing at the expiry of that term, the authority lapses and your agent has no further right to market the property or claim commission on a subsequent sale.</p>

      <p>Actively withdrawing before the authority expires is different. You are terminating the agreement early, which may carry implications depending on how the authority is worded. Some agency agreements include clauses that allow the agent to recover marketing costs incurred to the date of withdrawal. Read your authority carefully before you act, and if you are unsure, ask your solicitor to review it. Do not assume withdrawal is cost-free just because no sale occurred.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What you owe your agent when you withdraw</h2>
      <p>When a seller withdraws, the agent is typically entitled to recover any marketing costs that were agreed upfront and have already been incurred. If you authorised a marketing budget covering photography, copywriting, online listings, signboard, and print advertising, and those expenses have been paid out, your agent can claim reimbursement for those costs even if no sale results. The commission itself is generally not payable on a withdrawal, but marketing disbursements are a separate matter.</p>

      <p>The more complex scenario is the introduced buyer. If your agent introduced a buyer to your property during the campaign and that buyer later purchases it, your agent may have a claim to commission even if the sale occurs after you withdrew and re-listed through a different agent. This is not universal and depends on the specific wording of your authority and the applicable Queensland Property Occupations Act provisions. An agent who introduced a ready, willing, and able buyer during an active authority period may have a legitimate claim if that buyer ultimately buys, regardless of the timeline. Get advice before withdrawing if you are aware of active buyers your agent has introduced.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What withdrawal does to your days on market</h2>
      <p>This is where sellers often misunderstand the consequences. When you withdraw and re-list, the days on market counter resets. On the major portals, your property will appear as a new listing with zero days on market. That is the mechanical good news.</p>

      <p>The practical reality is more nuanced. Active buyers who attended your open homes, requested contracts, or inspected privately during the original campaign have already seen the property and formed an opinion about its price. When the listing reappears, those buyers know it has been on and off the market. For some, that creates urgency or renewed interest, particularly if the price has shifted or the presentation has improved. For others, the history creates scepticism: they assume the property failed to sell at the original price and they approach the re-listing with reduced conviction.</p>

      <p>The buyers you have not yet reached are the audience a re-listing genuinely resets for. New buyers who enter the market after your withdrawal will encounter the property fresh. The strength of your re-launch depends heavily on how large the active buyer pool has turned over during the gap.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to handle the messaging when you re-list</h2>
      <p>How you re-enter the market matters as much as when. A re-listing that looks identical to the original campaign, at a similar price point and with the same photographs, will struggle to create fresh momentum. Buyers will recognise it, and the absence of a clear reason to reconsider will limit interest.</p>

      <p>A strong re-launch has three distinguishing features. First, a genuine change in presentation: a refresh of styling, new photography, a renovation or improvement that gives buyers something new to respond to. Second, a price that reflects what the market actually told you during the original campaign, not a modest adjustment that still looks optimistic relative to the prior asking range. Third, enough time in between. A property that disappears and reappears within three or four weeks will not feel fresh to buyers who were active during the first campaign. In Brisbane's inner east, a gap of at least two months, and ideally three to four, gives the active buyer pool a chance to turn over sufficiently for the re-listing to land cleanly.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When to withdraw versus when to reduce and push through</h2>
      <p>Withdrawing is not always the right answer when a campaign is underperforming. Sometimes reducing the price and pushing through the end of the campaign is the more pragmatic choice, particularly if there is genuine buyer interest but a price gap, or if the vendor's circumstances make a drawn-out hiatus impractical.</p>

      <p>Withdrawal makes more sense when the feedback from the market is that the property itself needs work rather than just a price adjustment, when personal circumstances have genuinely changed and the sale no longer needs to proceed, or when market conditions have moved materially against you and waiting for an improvement is a realistic option given your timeframe.</p>

      <p>If the only issue is price and you have buyers who are interested at a number below your expectations, withdrawing and waiting rarely changes that dynamic. The buyers who exist in your market at your price point today will likely still be there in six months, and they will remember what the property was asking the first time around. A clear-eyed conversation with your agent about what the feedback is actually telling you will usually produce a more useful answer than instinctively deciding to withdraw when the campaign is not going as hoped.</p>

